canonical:
  title: 宰臣已下初度請復常膳不允
  author: 洪鈞
  language: lzh
  text: 孝當竭力喪以盡哀文公歠粥以居廬五月未嘗有命高宗宅憂而思道三載其惟不言後代已還淳風漸弛取應變隨時之義有以日易月之規日有萬機惟厥位固難虛也權臨庶政乃其勢不得已焉且以何心忍其鮮食卿等憫我追勞之甚恐其攝養之乖侑以珍餐誠雖迫於愛主在於朕意慙不勝於忸顔
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 宰臣已下初度請復常膳不允
  author: 洪鈞
  language: lzh
  text: 孝當竭力。喪以盡哀。文公歠粥以居廬五月。未嘗有命。高宗宅憂而思道三載。其惟不言。後代已還。淳風漸弛。取應變隨時之義。有以日易月之規。日有萬機。惟厥位固難虛也。權臨庶政。乃其勢不得已焉。且以何心。忍其鮮食。卿等憫我追勞之甚。恐其攝養之乖。侑以珍餐。誠雖迫於愛主。在於朕意。慙不勝於忸顔。
korean:
  title: 재신 이하가 첫 번째 상선을 회복하기를 청함을 윤허하지 아니함
  author: 홍균
  language: kor
  text: 효도를 함에는 마땅히 힘을 다하여서 해야 하고, 거상을 함에 있어서는 애통을 다해야 한다. 진나라 문공(文公)은 죽을 마시면서 다섯 달이나 여막에 있어 정치에 대한 명을 내리지 않았고, 은나라 고종(高宗)은 거상하면서 3년 동안 도(道)를 생각하고 아무 말씀을 하지 않았다. 후대에 내려와서는 순후한 풍조가 점점 해이해져 때를 따라 임기 응변해서 날로써 달을 바꾸는 규례가 있었다. 날마다 만기(萬機)가 있는 터에 그 자리를 진실로 비워두기가 어려운바, 권도(權道)로 서정(庶政)에 임함은 사세상 부득이한 일이다. 그러나 내 무슨 마음으로 차마 고기반찬을 먹겠는가.경들이 내가 너무 일을 고되게 함을 민망히 여기고 섭생(攝生)에 어긋남이 있을까 두려워하여 고기를 먹기를 권하였는데, 그 정성은 비록 임금을 사랑하는 지극한 정성이나, 짐의 심정으론 부끄러움을 이기지 못하겠도다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0330_010_0260&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Prime Minister and Court Officials Request That I Resume Eating Meat, Which I Cannot Allow
  author: Hong Gyun
  language: eng
  text: True filial piety demands we exhaust ourselves in its pursuit, and in mourning we must pour out our sorrow completely. Duke Wen of Jin drank only gruel while dwelling in his mourning hut for five months, issuing no commands on governance. King Gao of Shang sat in grief, contemplating the Way for three years, speaking not a word. Yet as ages passed, the pure customs grew thin and slack. Men began to bend with circumstance, to trade the day for the month's measure. With ten thousand matters pressing each day, how can one truly leave the throne vacant? To rule through expedience in these common affairs—such necessity admits no choice. And yet, what heart could I bear to take flesh and meat? My ministers pity me, seeing how I strain myself with labor, fearing my health grows frail from neglect. So they press fine dishes upon me, their devotion springing from their love of their sovereign. Yet in my heart, I cannot but blush with shame.
  footnotes:
    - Duke Wen of Jin and King Gao of Shang were exemplars of filial devotion in Chinese tradition, maintaining strict mourning practices
    - The phrase 'trading day for month' refers to a corruption of mourning protocols, where shorter periods were substituted for the proper duration
    - The speaker appears to be a king or high official who is maintaining mourning rites while burdened with state responsibilities
